Dr. Jorge M. Zuniga received a Master of Science and Ph.D. from the University of Nebraska-Lincoln. He is a member of The Association of Children's Prosthetic-Orthotic Clinics and the American College of Sports Medicine. He is currently an assistant professor at Creighton University in the Department of Exercise Science and Pre Health professions. His main research interests include evaluation of muscle function, neurophysiology, and development of low-cost 3D printed prosthetics, orthotics, and assitive devices. Dr. Zuniga is a scientist in the Department of Biomechanics, Biomechanics Research Building at the University of Nebraska Omaha. He has authored and co-authored over 70 manuscripts published in peer reviewed scientific journals. Dr. Zuniga and his research team developed a 3D printed prosthetic hand for children named Cyborg Beast (http://www.cyborgbeast.org). Robot dude from Ottawa, Canada

• Hardware
    • Using a MakerBot only because I got it as a "hand-me-down" - if I had ever gotten around to buying my own printer, I'd be using a more open-source-friendly printer.
    • To redeem myself, and to make it work as best as possible, I am running my own build of the latest Sailfish firmware on it, however! My changes are here: https://github.com/rpavlik/Sailfish-MightyBoardFirmware - some simple build system changes to make it easier to build on Windows (with the toolchain that comes with Atmel Studio 7), as well as updated SD card library (I did a bit of git magic, with a lot of rebasing and merge conflict resolution, to hopefully seamlessly combine the changes from the upstream SD card library used with the changes made in Sailfish itself)
    • Before I had a 3D printer, my computer-controlled construction tool was a Cricut Explore (again, unfortunately not open source friendly, but I got it on super-cheap clearance in a bundle that included the Bluetooth adapter) - which is still faster for some tasks, as long as those tasks can be performed by cutting cereal boxes (or things of that nature) very precisely :) It's a very useful and interesting tool (it's the newer generation, not limited to those cartridges - you can upload your own designs - but this also means there's very little third-party "innards" documentation online for it), and handy to be able to turn an SVG into a physical object - it's a shame that the company has an even more anti-open reputation than MakerBot.
  • Software Tools:
    • I've used more tools in the past (for general 3D purposes, etc) than I've listed in the rest of the bio - but the ones I've listed are the ones I've used for designing essentially "CNC"-like physical objects.

My Favorites: A mix of the items that I've designed that I'm able to share (things for personal, rather than work, use, typically) and prints of other peoples' designs that turned out particularly nice.

bio:
I was born in Zurich, Switzerland, grew up nearby. After finishing my studies in Electrical Engineering at the ETH in Zurich with a masters degree, I was working as a software developer - initially in semiconductor industries, and later many years in life science. Designing and creating innovative software, interacting with customers, and managing a small team of software developers was my big pleasure. As a hobby I aleays designed and experimented with model airplanes. When 3d-printing became commonly available, a door for a new type of creativity was opened. I had to open this door, and immediately my focus was attracted by mechanical watches and machines, and I stopped my former job.

I believe, future mechanical objects will be highly customisable - not only engraving but also mechanical function. Hardware becomes Software.

By sharing valuable functional designs for free, I'd like to demonstrate the future potential of the new technology. If somebody likes to support my work, I have no objections for a donation :-)
